04464nam a22005295i 9780773576827DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20092009xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1399976437  a97807735768277 a10.1515/97807735768272doi  a(DE-B1597)655442  a(OCoLC)1088664276  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aHV6545 ǂb W43 2009eb 7aPSY0370002bisacsh04a362.28/09931 aWeaver, John C., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSadly Troubled History :bThe Meanings of Suicide in the Modern Age /cJohn C. Weaver. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2009] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (464 p.) :b20 photos  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMcGill-Queen's/Associated Medical Services Studies in the History of Medicine, Health, and Society ;v3300tFront Matter -- tContents -- tTables and Graphs -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- tTheory, Conjecture, and Politics -- tSuicide as a Gauge for the Times: The Nineteenth Century -- tEpistemic Communities and the Suicide Problem: The Twentieth Century -- tRates, Society, and Motives -- tBearings on a Temporal Compass: Rates, Seasons, Cohorts, and Motives -- tWork and Troubles: Men and Motives -- tSorrows and Burdens: Women and Motives -- tRationality, Psyche, and Treatment -- tWhat Becomes of the Broken-Hearted? Intentions, Decisions, and Acts -- tManaging Mental Crises: Psychiatry and Suicidal Patients -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMore people die by suicide each year than by homicide, wars, and terrorist attacks combined. Witnesses and survivors are left perplexed and troubled. Doctors, clinical psychologists, and social workers try to deal with it through their professional routines; sociologists and psychiatrists attempt to provide theoretical explanations of it. In a study of nearly 7000 suicides from 1900 to 1950 in New Zealand and Queensland, Australia, John Weaver documents the challenges that ordinary people experienced during turbulent times and, using witnesses' testimony, death bed statements, and suicide notes, reconstructs individuals' thoughts as they decide whether to endure their suffering. Bridging social and medical history, Weaver presents an intellectual and political history of suicide studies, a revealing construction and deconstruction of suicide rates, a discussion of gender, life stages, and socio-economic circumstances in relation to suicide patterns, reflections on reasoning processes and intent, and society's reactions to suicide, including medical intervention. A Sadly Troubled History marshals thousands of suicide inquests, replete with observations on the anxieties of unemployment, the heartbreak of romantic disappointment, the pain of domestic turmoil, and the torments of mental illness, to demonstrate that history - although, like biochemistry, sociology, psychology, and psychiatry, reliant on remarkable yet imperfect information - can contribute to a better understanding of the suicidal act and its motives.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aPSYCHOLOGY / Suicide.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077357682740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773576827423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773576827/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles